The Deputy National Chair­man of the People’s Demo­cratic Party (PDP), Taofeek Arapaja, and Chairman of Pacesetter Transportation Service Company, Dare Adeleke, have been accused of preventing some delegates from participating at ongoing primary to elect candidate for Ibadan South East House of Assembly Constituency II. The party primary that is ongoing at the Saint John Pri­mary School, Alake, Academy, Ibadan, the state capital, some delegates while speaking with journalists alleged that Ara­paja and Adeleke were mov­ing around the venue of the primary with military men, ought supposed to provide security for delegates, but shooting into air sporadically to intimidate their perceived opposition within the party. One of the delegates, Sa­kirat Sheu, alleged that she was on queue inside the school when Arapaja and Adeleke came in with soldiers and sent her and others out of the school. -Advertisement- According to her, “We were already on the queue when deputy national chairman, Ambassador Taofeek Arapa­ja, and Dare Adeleke came and forced some of us out. The soldiers were shooting into the sky to scare us; we had no option than to go out, preventing us from perform­ing our civic responsibility to the party.